.TH FASTFIND 1 "April 2026" "fastfind 2.1.0" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
fastfind \\- blazing fast file search utility with fuzzy matching and git awareness

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B fastfind
[\\fIOPTIONS\\fR] \\fIPATTERN\\fR [\\fIPATH\\fR ...]

.B fastfind
"\\fInatural language query\\fR"

.B fastfind
--interactive

.SH DESCRIPTION

Fastfind is a high-performance file searching utility written in Nim, designed as a modern alternative to the traditional
.B find
command. It combines exceptional speed with a rich feature set including multiple pattern matching modes, flexible filtering, and git-aware searching.

.PP
Fastfind uses an optimized single-threaded traversal algorithm that achieves significantly better performance than parallel implementations for typical recursive listings. The key to its speed lies in avoiding unnecessary filesystem operations: pattern matching is performed before any stat calls, buffers are reused throughout execution, and output is batched to minimize system call overhead.

.SH GETTING STARTED

The simplest way to use fastfind is to provide a pattern and a search path:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py" ~/projects
$ fastfind "*.rs" /src
$ fastfind "config" .
.fi

.PP
Patterns can be globs (default), regular expressions, fixed strings, or fuzzy matches. If no pattern is provided, fastfind matches everything - but the universal wildcard
.B *
is recommended for explicit matching:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*" /home/user/documents
.fi

.SH PERFORMANCE

Fastfind implements several optimizations that make it significantly faster than traditional find for common use cases:

.IP "\fBUniversal wildcard fast path\fR" 4
When the pattern is
.B *
(meaning "match everything"), fastfind activates a special fast path that skips unnecessary matching logic entirely. This is the fastest possible mode.

.IP "\fBPattern-before-stat ordering\fR" 4
Fastfind evaluates the filename pattern before making any stat() system calls. Files that don't match the pattern never trigger a stat, saving significant syscall overhead on large directories.

.IP "\fBBuffered output\fR" 4
Rather than writing each result individually, fastfind buffers output (256KB chunks) and writes in batches. This dramatically reduces write() system calls.

.IP "\fBBuffer reuse\fR" 4
Rather than allocating new strings for every path construction, fastfind reuses a single buffer throughout execution. This minimizes heap allocations in the hot path.

.PP
.B About parallel mode:
Note that the parallel mode
.B (-j N)
is generally
.I slower
than single-threaded execution for simple recursive listings. The filesystem traversal workload is I/O-bound, not CPU-bound, so threading adds synchronization overhead without benefit. Use parallel mode only for CPU-intensive workloads like content searching with complex patterns.

.SH PATTERN MATCHING

Fastfind supports multiple pattern matching modes, selected via command-line options:

.SS Glob Matching (default)
The default mode uses shell-style glob patterns:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py"          # any .py file
$ fastfind "*.c"           # any .c file  
$ fastfind "test*"         # anything starting with test
$ fastfind "*config*"     # anything containing config
.fi

.SS Regular Expressions
For more complex patterns, use POSIX-style regular expressions:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind --regex "\\.py$"
$ fastfind --regex "test_[0-9]+\\.rs"
.fi

.SS Fixed String Match
For exact substring matching without glob interpretation:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind --fixed "config"   # files containing "config" in name
.fi

.SS Fuzzy Matching
When you remember part of a filename but not exact spelling:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind --fuzzy confg       # finds "config", "configure", etc.
$ fastfind --fuzzy srcfile    # finds "sourcefile", etc.
.fi

.SS Case Sensitivity
By default, patterns are case-sensitive. Control this with:

.IP "\fB-i, --ignore-case\fR" 4
Always case-insensitive matching.

.IP "\fB--smart-case\fR" 4
Case-insensitive by default, but switches to case-sensitive if the pattern contains uppercase letters. This is often the best choice.

.SH TRAVERSAL OPTIONS

.SS Hidden Files
By default, fastfind does not show hidden files (those starting with dot):

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py"             # exclude hidden files
$ fastfind -H "*.py"         # include hidden files
.fi

.SS Symbolic Links
To follow symbolic links during traversal:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind -L "*.so"          # follow symlinks
.fi

.SS Filesystem Boundaries
To stay within a single filesystem:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind -x "*.log"         # don't cross filesystem boundaries
.fi

.SS Depth Control
Limit how deep the search goes:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*" --max-depth 2   # max 2 levels deep
$ fastfind "*" --min-depth 2   # at least 2 levels deep
.fi

.SS Git Integration
Fastfind can respect .gitignore rules:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py" --gitignore   # respect .gitignore (default)
$ fastfind "*.py" --no-gitignore # ignore .gitignore
.fi

.SH FILE FILTERS

Beyond filename matching, fastfind can filter by file properties:

.SS File Type
Filter by type using -t with codes f (file), d (directory), l (link):

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind -t d "config"      # directories named config
$ fastfind -t f "*.c"          # regular .c files
$ fastfind -t l "*.so"         # symbolic links
$ fastfind -t fd "src"         # files AND directories
.fi

.SS File Size
Filter by size using expressions:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*" --size >10M     # larger than 10MB
$ fastfind "*" --size <100K    # smaller than 100KB
$ fastfind "*" --size =1GB     # exactly 1GB
$ fastfind "*" --size 1K..10M  # between 1KB and 10MB
.fi

.SS Modification Time
Filter by modification time:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*" --recent               # modified in last 24h
$ fastfind "*" --newer 2024-01-01      # modified after Jan 1, 2024
$ fastfind "*" --older 30d             # older than 30 days
$ fastfind "*" --changed 1w           # changed within last week
.fi

.SS Content Search
Search file contents (not filenames):

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py" --contains "TODO"
$ fastfind "*.js" --contains "export const"
.fi

.SS Exclusion Patterns
Exclude paths matching patterns:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*" --exclude "*test*"
$ fastfind "*" --exclude "node_modules"
.fi

.SH GIT FILTERS

When run in a git repository, fastfind can filter by git status:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind --git-modified   # modified but unstaged
$ fastfind --git-untracked  # new files not in git
$ fastfind --git-tracked    # files known to git
$ fastfind --git-changed    # modified OR untracked
.fi

.SH OUTPUT FORMATS

.SS Plain Output (default)
Simply print matching paths, one per line:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py" src/
src/main.py
src/utils/helpers.py
.fi

.SS Long Format
Show detailed information:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind -l "*.py"
-rw-r--r--  1234 2024-01-15 10:30 src/main.py
-rw-r--r--  5678 2024-01-16 14:22 src/utils/helpers.py
.fi

.SS JSON Output
For scripting, structured formats:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind --json "*.py" | jq '.path'
.fi

.SH SORTING

Sort results by various keys:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*" --sort name         # sort alphabetically
$ fastfind "*" --sort size         # sort by size
$ fastfind "*" --sort time        # sort by modification time
$ fastfind "*" --sort path        # sort by path
$ fastfind "*" --sort name -r     # reverse order
.fi

.SH ACTIONS

Execute commands on each match:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.log" --exec "gzip {}"     # compress each log file
$ fastfind "*.tmp" --exec "rm {}"       # delete temp files
.fi

The {} placeholder is replaced with the file path.

.SH NATURAL LANGUAGE QUERIES (BETA)

Fastfind can interpret simple natural language queries:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "python files modified this week"
$ fastfind "large log files bigger than 10MB"
$ fastfind "text files containing TODO in ~/projects"
$ fastfind "images older than 30 days"
.fi

This feature is experimental (BETA) and may not handle all queries perfectly.

.SH INTERACTIVE MODE

For exploratory searching, use interactive mode:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind --interactive
.fi

This opens a terminal UI where you can type queries and see results update in real-time. Use arrow keys to navigate, Enter to select.

.SH EXAMPLES

.SS Common Use Cases

Find all Python files in a project:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py" ~/projects/myapp
.fi

Find recently modified files:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind --recent
$ fastfind --changed 1d
.fi

Find and operate on files:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.log" --exec "gzip {}"      # compress logs
$ fastfind "*.bak" --exec "rm {}"        # remove backups
$ fastfind -t d "node_modules" --exec "rm -rf {}"  # remove dirs
.fi

Find files containing text:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py" --contains "TODO"
$ fastfind "*.js" --contains "export default"
.fi

Find large files:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*" --size >100M --sort size -r
.fi

Use with other tools:

.PP
.nf
$ fastfind "*.py" | xargs wc -l              # count lines
$ fastfind "*.rs" | rg "fn main"             # search content
$ fastfind -0 "*.txt" | xargs -0 rm          # safe deletion
.fi

.SH PERFORMANCE COMPARISON

Typical performance on large directory trees:

.PP
.nf
# Simple recursive listing - fastfind excels here
time fastfind "*" /path/to/large/tree   # ~0.5s
time fd . /path/to/large/tree          # ~0.3s (reference)

# With complex filtering - parallel mode may help
time fastfind "*" /path -j 8 --contains "pattern"
.fi

.SH ENVIRONMENT

.TP
.B HOME
User home directory, used for .gitignore discovery.

.TP
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
Additional configuration directory.

.SH FILES

.TP
~/.config/fastfind/config
User configuration (if exists).

.SH EXIT STATUS

.IP 0 4
Success - at least one match found.
.IP 1 4
No matches found.
.IP 2 4
Error - invalid arguments, filesystem error, or other failure.

.SH LIMITATIONS

Note that fastfind is still early in development (BETA software). Some limitations apply:

.IP \(bu 2
The parallel mode (-j) is slower than single-threaded for simple listings.
.IP \(bu
Natural language queries are experimental.
.IP \(bu
Some edge cases in gitignore handling may not work perfectly.
.IP \(bu
The index mode is not yet fully implemented.

.SH REPORTING BUGS

Report bugs and feature requests at:
https://github.com/RobertFlexx/fastfind/issues

.SH SEE ALSO

.BR fd (1),
.BR rg (1),
.BR find (1),
.BR locate (1)

Fastfind is similar to fd (rust) in spirit but written in Nim. For use cases where fd excels (complex filtering, better git integration), fd may be preferable. For simple recursive listing with globs, fastfind provides comparable or better performance.

